Accessibility Preferences (Ctrl + Alt + A)
English (USA)
This profile enables All in One Accessibility screen-reader. By using a screen reader, information from the device is announced in clear speech allowing a blind user to access devices on an equal footing with sighted counterparts.
This profile enables motor-impaired persons to operate the website using the keyboard. Users can also use shortcuts to jump to specific elements.
This profile adjusts the website so that it is accessible to the majority of visual impairments such as Degrading Eyesight, Tunnel Vision, Cataracts, Glaucoma, and others.
This profile adjusts website colors to suit individuals with the most prevalent forms of color blindness. Specific color blindness adjustments can be found within the 'color-blindness' settings.
This profile changes the font style, size, and spacing in order to make it easier for people with dyslexia to read the website content.
This profile provides various assistive features to help users with cognitive disabilities, such as Autism, Dyslexia, CVA, and others, to focus on the essential elements more easily.
This profile enables people with epilepsy to safely use the website by eliminating the risk of seizures resulting from flashing or blinking animations and risky color combinations.
This profile significantly reduces distractions and noise to help people with ADHD and Neurodivergent people browse, read, and focus on the essential elements more easily.

Mission

Phishing Debrief

Hello Agent. A number of false emails are being send daily to headquarters. These emails are made to look like they are being sent by other agents. We have reason to believe these emails are from Evil Corp. Your mission is to learn how to spot fake emails, and help us spot the real emails from the fakes. Good luck.

The Boss liked my last one so much, he let me do it again! This time, we are covering the history of emailing.

Before the invention of emails, people used telegraphs and letters to write each other from far away. But, in 1965 at MIT, the first program to ever use email was invented. It was called Mailbox, and could only be used on the same computer.

Then the U.S. Department of Defense made ARPANET, a network that was able to send the first message from one computer to another.

The stage was set for a new mailing revolution, BUT they weren't sure how to address the messages so that they would be able to always go where they were supposed to?

Ray Tomlinson figured it out! He created the @ symbol for use in online mailing. After that, Internet Service Provider (ISPs) began to connect regular people, and the rest is history!

After that, companies like AOL (America Online), Hotmail, Yahoo, and eventually Google stepped in to provide easy access for everyday people to send their own messages. Starting at 1997 there were 55 million users, but it exploded to 400 million in 1999 and today is something nearly  everyone has.

Which Is How we got here

 

Sending and receiving emails works different that sticking it in an envelope and licking the stamp.

Wait, it is? You don't need stamps? Oops...

Sending and receiving emails works different that sticking it in an envelope and licking the stamp. Come one, let's get in the thick of it!

Let's say that you have a picture of a cute dog you want to email to someone in your family. You type it up on your computer and then soon as you hit send, it's on its way.

Internet

SMTP

First, your message goes from your computer to the server, and then to the internet. From there, it continues the same way on the other end.

Wow, that's longer than I thought. But wait, what is that SMTP thing?

Oh, that's just the mailman. They let the messages go where they need to and are the whole reason that servers can connect to each other.

Hi! I'm Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP). Great to meetcha! These down here are my helpers, IMAP and POP3. Without them I wouldn't get all my work done!

IMAP (Internet Mail Access Protocol)

POP3 (Post Office Protocol 3)

I work with copies that can stay on the server!

I delete the message from the server. No need to be sharing here.

I know this one! My dad and I used to pack up and go to the lake real early-

Wait, wait! That's not what phishing is, Agent P. That's FISHING. Phishing is using fake emails to fish out people, not fish.

Whoops. But why would someone do a thing like that? I send things like baby capybara pictures. Who wants to steal that?

But Not all is lost

That's terrible! How can I protect myself? Help, Agent Q!

Here are a few things you can do. Never share your personal information online, and keep an eye out for fakes.

OMG, I'm totally not faking <3

Suuuure. We are on to you, Goon. We won't fall for any tricks.

WHAT? Totally can't be!

Take a look at these two emails.

Sus! It's an imposter email!

Fake emails will try to make you uncomfortable as possible, rushing you to take action. If anything rushes you, that's a good right to slow down and get an adult.

Often, phishers won't actually have any information about you, so they will try to address you without showing any information about your account.

Websites tend to be more professional and fancy about how they go about their emails. Good example is here, where the link, not only isn't to Microsoft, but has a mispelling.

Phishers love making mispellings and other simple to fix errors. Not all of them do this, but if you see it, that's a pretty red flag to have someone older check it with you.

But there's one more tiiiiiny one. Have you seen it yet?

Other details, like wrong domain name or a misplaced slash can give away many hacker emails. Just be careful because not all of them do this either.

No?

I can't see it!

WHAAAAAAAAAAAT!

Sometimes something that tiny may be the only thing that can suggest it's fake. That's why when anything asks you to change your password and you aren't sure, there are two things you should do.

 

One is get a trusted adult to help you, and if you both still aren't sure, do not click the link. Instead, change your password from the website off of google or from your existing bookmarks, not the email.

Especially if it's a message you didn't know was coming ahead of time, always be suspicious!

Phishing isn't just official looking emails. It could be anyone. Someone pretending to be your grandma, your friend, all sorts of crazy things!

Look like an investigator, with a magnifying glass! That right there isn't an m. It's an r and an n put together.
